'''Right to repair''' is a legal right for owners of devices and equipment to freely [[Maintenance|maintain]], [[Repairability|repair]], or modify products such as automobiles, electronics, and farm equipment.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Right to repair |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/right-to-repair |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250522164712/https://www.britannica.com/topic/right-to-repair |archive-date=May 22, 2025 |access-date=December 25, 2025 |work=Encyclopedia Britannica |language=en |url-status=live }}</ref>

Common obstacles to repair include requirements to use only the manufacturer's maintenance services, restrictions on access to tools and components, and software barriers. These obstacles represent a repair monopoly, an [[Aftermarket (merchandise)|aftermarket]] [[monopoly]] where a company controls the market for repairing and maintaining their products, making it difficult or even impossible for anyone to be able to fix them. This can take the form of making it challenging or prohibitively expensive for individuals or independent third parties to get access to parts, manuals, or diagnostic tools. The purpose of repair monopolies is to force customers to either use the manufacturer's own repair services or purchase new equipment from the manufacturer.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Galaz|first1=Victor|title=Dark Machines: How Artificial Intelligence, Digitalization and Automation is Changing our Living Planet|date=December 16, 2024 |publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-040-26223-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j60vEQAAQBAJ&dq=%22repair+monopoly%22&pg=RA3-PT87|language=en}}</ref>

Repair monopolies have been found to lead to higher prices, increased delays, reduced serviceability, and less choice for consumers.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perzanowski|first1=Aaron|title=The Right to Repair: Reclaiming the Things We Own|date=February 8, 2022|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-108-94382-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gNhaEAAAQBAJ&dq=repair+monopoly&pg=PA337|language=en}}</ref> Proponents for the right to repair point to the benefits in affordability, sustainability, and availability of critical supplies in times of crisis. There is a social movement of citizens putting pressure on their governments to enact laws protecting a right to repair.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ozturkcan|first1=Selcen|title=The right-to-repair movement: Sustainability and consumer rights|journal=Journal of Information Technology Teaching Cases|date=2024|volume=14|issue=2|pages=217–223|doi=10.1177/20438869231178037|doi-access=free}}</ref>

== Impacts ==
While initially majorly driven by automotive consumers protection agencies and the automotive after sales service industry, the discussion of establishing a right to repair not only for vehicles but for any kind of electronic product gained traction as consumer electronics such as smartphones and computers became universally available, causing broken and used electronics to become the fastest growing waste stream.<ref name="Chen" /><ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Semuels |first1=Alana |date=May 23, 2019 |title=The World Has an E-Waste Problem |url=https://time.com/5594380/world-electronic-waste-problem/ |access-date=September 29, 2021 |magazine=Time |language=en |archive-date=May 12, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240512225728/https://time.com/5594380/world-electronic-waste-problem/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> Today it's estimated that more than half of the population of the western world has one or more used or broken electronic devices at home that are not introduced back into the market due to a lack of affordable repair.<ref>{{cite web |last=Thobe |first=Fabian V. |date=October 4, 2017 |title=Fino a 2.6 Miliardi di Euro & 1 Miliardo di KG CO2 sprecati dagli smartphone che gli italiani non usano più |url=https://www.ricompro.it/blog/fino-a-26-miliardi-di-euro-1-miliardo-di-kg-co2-sprecati-dagli-smartphone-che-gli-italiani-non-usano-pi/ |website=riCompro |language=it |type=Blog |access-date=May 11, 2024 |archive-date=July 13, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240713105436/https://www.ricompro.it/blog/fino-a-26-miliardi-di-euro-1-miliardo-di-kg-co2-sprecati-dagli-smartphone-che-gli-italiani-non-usano-pi/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In addition to the consumer goods, healthcare equipment repair access made news at the start of the [[COVID-19 pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic in 2020]], when hospitals had trouble getting maintenance for some critical high-demand medical equipment, most notably ventilators.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=He |first1=Shuhan |last2=Lai |first2=Debbie |last3=Lee |first3=Jarone |date=April 2021 |title=The medical right to repair: the right to save lives |journal=The Lancet |language=en |volume=397 |issue=10281 |pages=1260–1261 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(21)00445-1|pmid=33773116 |pmc=7990498 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Perlow |first1=Jason |last2=Cipriani |first2=Jason |date=July 7, 2021 |title=Your right to repair: How COVID sent businesses, hospitals, and consumers to the breaking point |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/the-right-to-repair-covid-19-sending-businesses-hospitals-and-consumers-to-the-tipping-point/ |access-date=December 20, 2023 |website=[[ZDNET]] |language=en |archive-date=April 1, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240401011929/https://www.zdnet.com/article/the-right-to-repair-covid-19-sending-businesses-hospitals-and-consumers-to-the-tipping-point/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Condon |first=Stephanie |date=August 6, 2020 |title=Lawmakers call for "right to repair" medical equipment during COVID-19 pandemic |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/lawmakers-call-for-right-to-repair-medical-equipment-during-covid-19-pandemic/ |access-date=December 20, 2023 |website=ZDNET |language=en |archive-date=August 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200807015257/https://www.zdnet.com/article/lawmakers-call-for-right-to-repair-medical-equipment-during-covid-19-pandemic/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

The pandemic has also been credited with helping to grow the right-to-repair movement since many repair shops were closed.<ref name="spreading">{{Cite news |date=November 19, 2021 |title=Why is the "right to repair" gadgets and machines spreading? |url=https://www.economist.com/the-economist-explains/2021/11/19/why-is-the-right-to-repair-gadgets-and-machines-spreading |access-date=July 15, 2024 |newspaper=The Economist |issn=0013-0613 |archive-date=July 15, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240715231820/https://www.economist.com/the-economist-explains/2021/11/19/why-is-the-right-to-repair-gadgets-and-machines-spreading |url-status=live }}</ref> ''The Economist'' also cites the expectation that owners of products should be able to repair them as a sense of moral justice or [[property rights]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=September 30, 2017 |title=How digital devices challenge the nature of ownership |url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/2017/09/30/how-digital-devices-challenge-the-nature-of-ownership |access-date=July 15, 2024 |newspaper=The Economist |issn=0013-0613}}</ref> Those fighting against [[planned obsolescence]] have also taken note of when repair costs exceeds replacement costs because the companies that created the product have retained a [[monopoly]] on its repair, driving up prices.<ref name="spreading" />

== Definition ==
{{See also|Right to property|Repairability}}

Right to repair refers to the concept that end users of technical, electronic or automotive devices should be allowed to freely repair these products. Some notable aspects of a product include:<ref>{{Cite news |last=Park |first=Miles |date=March 22, 2018 |title=Sustainable shopping: if you really, truly need a new phone, buy one with replaceable parts |url=http://theconversation.com/sustainable-shopping-if-you-really-truly-need-a-new-phone-buy-one-with-replaceable-parts-93069 |website=The Conversation |archive-date=May 30, 2024 |access-date=May 11, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240530111256/https://theconversation.com/sustainable-shopping-if-you-really-truly-need-a-new-phone-buy-one-with-replaceable-parts-93069 |url-status=live }}</ref>

# the device should be constructed and designed in a manner that allows repairs to be made easily;
# end users and independent repair providers should be able to access original spare parts and necessary tools (software as well as physical tools) at fair market conditions;
# repairs should, by design, be possible and not be hindered by software programming; and
# the [[repairability]] of a device should be clearly communicated by the manufacturer.

Some goals of the right to repair are to favor repair instead of replacement, and make such repairs more affordable leading to a more sustainable economy and reduction in electronic waste.<ref name="Wirecutter">{{cite web |title=What You Should Know About Right to Repair |url=https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/blog/what-is-right-to-repair/ |website=Wirecutter: Reviews for the Real World |date=July 15, 2021 |access-date=September 29, 2021 |archive-date=June 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230605182432/https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/blog/what-is-right-to-repair/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Chen">{{cite web |last1=Chen |first1=Brian X. |title=Why You Should Care About Your Right to Repair Gadgets |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/07/14/technology/personaltech/right-to-repair-iphones-android.html |website=The New York Times |date=July 14, 2021 |access-date=September 29, 2021 |archive-date=June 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230605182523/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/07/14/technology/personaltech/right-to-repair-iphones-android.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=King |first=Rosie |date=July 10, 2021 |title=It's getting easier to throw out broken technology, and harder to repair it — but an Australian movement is pushing back |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2021-07-10/act-right-to-repair-movement-growing-in-australia/100283348 |access-date=August 9, 2021 |website=www.abc.net.au |language=en-AU |archive-date=December 30, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231230214302/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2021-07-10/act-right-to-repair-movement-growing-in-australia/100283348 |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Repair-friendly design ===
{{See also|Design for the environment|Planned obsolescence}}
The use of glue or proprietary screws can make repairs more difficult.<ref name="Wirecutter" /> In general, proprietary parts and accessories can make products more difficult to repair, such as [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s "Lightning" charging ports and adapters, which require a non-standard process to repair, leading the European Union to standardize charging ports for small devices, requiring all devices to use [[USB-C]].<ref name="Cooper">{{Cite web |last=Cooper |first=Daniel |date=December 27, 2023 |title=The Right to Repair movement won its biggest victories in 2023 |url=https://www.engadget.com/the-right-to-repair-movement-won-its-biggest-victories-in-2023-143010331.html |access-date=April 24, 2024 |website=Engadget |language=en-US |archive-date=April 24, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240424211125/https://www.engadget.com/the-right-to-repair-movement-won-its-biggest-victories-in-2023-143010331.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Accessible spare parts and tools ===
Parts and tools needed to make repairs, should be available to everyone, including consumers.<ref name="Wirecutter" />

=== Software ===
'''Parts pairing''' <!-- bold because it is the target of redirect --> or '''Serialization''' prevents parts being swapped without a password that they provide to preferred technicians.<ref name="Cooper" /> This and other new ways to lock devices, including [[digital rights management]], have become increasingly popular among manufacturers.<ref>{{Cite web |last=De Leon |first=Nicholas |date=October 26, 2018 |title=It's Now Okay to Bypass DRM Software to Fix Gadgets, but Right-to-Repair Fight Isn't Over |url=https://www.consumerreports.org/electronics/now-okay-to-bypass-drm-software-locks-but-right-to-repair-fight-not-over/ |access-date=August 10, 2021 |website=Consumer Reports |language=en-US |archive-date=August 10, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210810143443/https://www.consumerreports.org/electronics/now-okay-to-bypass-drm-software-locks-but-right-to-repair-fight-not-over/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Using approved parts can increase the cost of the repair, leading many consumers to speed up their upgrade cycle to a new device.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Casserly |first=Martyn |date=November 17, 2020 |title=Right to Repair laws may soon make Apple change iPhone design |url=https://www.techadvisor.com/news/mobile-phone/will-right-repair-change-smartphone-design-3798101/ |website=[[Tech Advisor]] |access-date=May 11, 2024 |archive-date=April 27, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220427170826/https://www.techadvisor.com/news/mobile-phone/will-right-repair-change-smartphone-design-3798101/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In addition to access to software updates, the ability to install third-party software is also mentioned as a major goal, which would, for example, allow some devices to be adapted over time.<ref name="Wirecutter" />

=== Transparency ===
Manuals and design schematics should be freely available and help consumers know how to repair their devices.<ref name="Wirecutter" /><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Marshall |first=Aarian |date=October 20, 2022 |title=High-Tech Cars Are Killing the Auto Repair Shop |url=https://www.wired.com/story/high-tech-cars-killing-the-traditional-auto-repair-shop/ |access-date=April 28, 2024 |magazine=Wired |language=en-US |issn=1059-1028}}</ref>
