== History ==
{{Globalize|date=March 2023|2=US|section}}
[[File:Electric lightbulb, Paris.jpg|thumb|The [[Phoebus cartel]] is often claimed to be an example of [[planned obsolescence]].]]
The strategy to continuously change products to create continuous demand for the latest generation was pursued at a large scale by [[General Motors]] executive [[Alfred P. Sloan]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Yanes |first1=Javier |title=The Origin and Myths of Planned Obsolescence |url=https://www.bbvaopenmind.com/en/technology/innovation/origin-and-myths-of-planned-obsolescence/ |website=Open Mind by BBVA |date=September 11, 2020 |publisher=BBVA Group |access-date=September 11, 2020 |archive-date=April 18, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230418225259/https://www.bbvaopenmind.com/en/technology/innovation/origin-and-myths-of-planned-obsolescence/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Strauss |first1=Ilana |title=How GM Invented Planned Obsolescence |url=https://www.treehugger.com/how-planned-obsolescence-began-4856701 |website=Tree Hugger |publisher=Dotdash by About, Inc. |access-date=July 28, 2021 |date=December 7, 2018 |archive-date=June 1, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230601194748/https://www.treehugger.com/how-planned-obsolescence-began-4856701 |url-status=live }}</ref> GM overtook Ford as the biggest American automaker and planned obsolescence with annual variants of a product became widely adopted across industries in the American economy, eventually becoming adopted by Ford by 1933.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Slade |first1=Giles |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YMoxdac6J-cC&q=%E2%80%9CPsychological+obsolescence+was+now+the+rule+for+U.S.+automakers.+And+because+car+production+was+America%E2%80%99s+flagship+industry%2C+this+lesson+was+quickly+copied+in+all+other+areas+of+manufacturing.%22&pg=PA47 |title=Made to break : technology and obsolescence in America |date=2006 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=0674025725 |location=Cambridge, Mass. |pages=42–48 |access-date=July 25, 2021}}</ref><ref name="Strasser">{{cite book |last1=Strasser |first1=Susan |title=Waste and want: a social history of trash |date=1999 |publisher=Metropolitan Books |isbn=0805065121 |edition=1st |location=New York |page=220}}</ref>

The car industry was at the forefront of establishing the concept of certified repair: starting from the 1910s, Ford established certified dealerships and service networks to promote parts made by Ford instead of independent repair shops and often after-sales parts. Ford also pushed for standardized pricing among certified repair shops, making flat fees mandatory even for different repairs. The combination of annual updates to cars and components made it more difficult for independent repair shops to maintain a stock of parts.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McIntyre |first1=Stephen L. |date=April 1, 2000 |title=The Failure of Fordism: Reform of the Automobile Repair Industry, 1913–1940 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/25147500 |journal=[[Technology and Culture]] |volume=41 |issue=2 |pages=269–299 |doi=10.1353/tech.2000.0075 |jstor=25147500 |s2cid=109379833 |access-date=July 25, 2021 |url-access=subscription |archive-date=April 14, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230414172619/https://www.jstor.org/stable/25147500 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Strasser" />

A couple of court cases have required products with repaired or refurbished components to be labeled as "used."<ref>{{cite journal |date=January 1, 1939 |title=Unfair Competition—Reconditioning Used Goods—Permissible Limits of Resale of Patented or Trademarked Articles |url=https://journals.library.wustl.edu/lawreview/article/id/7377/ |journal=[[Washington University Law Quarterly]] |volume=24 |issue=2 |page=238 |archive-date=May 11, 2024 |access-date=May 11, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240511070538/https://journals.library.wustl.edu/lawreview/article/id/7377/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=O'Neil |first1=Michael |date=July 1, 1965 |title=Patents – Contributory Infringement – History and Trend: Convertible Top Cases |url=https://via.library.depaul.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=3336&context=law-review |journal=DePaul Law Review |language=En |publisher=DePaul University |volume=14 |issue=2 |pages=473–478 |access-date=July 28, 2021 |archive-date=March 1, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230301104308/https://via.library.depaul.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=3336&context=law-review |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 1947, a business owner was refurbishing old spark plugs and reselling them. However, he was reselling them under a trademarked name. This led to a lawsuit that provided the framework for legislation that would provide a right to resell repaired or refurbished items, as long as they were labelled correctly.

''[https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/331/125/ Champion Spark Plug Co. v. Sanders]'' provided the basis of FTC guidelines which provides an uninfringeable right to resell repaired or refurbished items as long as they were labeled as such. The decision also provided the framework for trademark guidelines regarding the resale of used goods under a trademarked namesake.

[https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-16/chapter-I/subchapter-B/part-20?toc=1 FTC guidelines Title 16, Chapter I, Subchapter B, Part 20] provides guidance and regulations on the labeling of items that have been “rebuilt”, “refurbished”, or “re-manufactured” in order to prevent unfair competitive advantage in selling components in the automobile industry. This guideline hence allowed businesses the ability to repair items, for resale later.

Some manufacturers shifted towards more repairable designs. [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], which rose quickly to become one of the largest computer manufacturers, sold the first computers with circuit board descriptions, easy-to-swap components, and clear repair instructions, but has since developed a reputation for imposing strict repair restrictions on its products.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kan |first1=Michael |title=Apple Co-Founder Steve Wozniak Publicly Backs Right to Repair |url=https://www.pcmag.com/news/apple-co-founder-steve-wozniak-publicly-backs-right-to-repair |access-date=July 26, 2021 |publisher=PC Mag |date=July 8, 2021 |archive-date=March 1, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230301104909/https://www.pcmag.com/news/apple-co-founder-steve-wozniak-publicly-backs-right-to-repair |url-status=live }}</ref>

Copyright with regard to computer software source code also became a front on the limitation of repairability. In the U.S., the [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act]] of 1998 prohibits repairs unless granted an exception, and has been used to block repairs as software became more common in a range of devices and appliances.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gault |first1=Matthew |date=January 4, 2021 |title=It Is Time, Yet Again, to Beg for the Right to Repair |url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/it-is-time-yet-again-to-beg-for-the-right-to-repair/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210614123342/https://vice.com/en/article/m7ape4/it-is-time-yet-again-to-beg-for-the-right-to-repair |archive-date=June 14, 2021 |access-date=September 19, 2021 |website=Vice.com |publisher=Vice Media Group |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mirr |first1=Nicholas A. |date=July 1, 2020 |title=Defending the Right to Repair: An Argument for Federal Legislation Guaranteeing the Right to Repair |url=https://ilr.law.uiowa.edu/print/volume-105-issue-5/defending-the-right-to-repair-an-argument-for-federal-legislation-guaranteeing-the-right-to-repair/ |journal=Iowa Law Review |volume=105 |issue=5 |pages=2393–2424 |access-date=July 27, 2021 |archive-date=April 18, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230418203344/https://ilr.law.uiowa.edu/print/volume-105-issue-5/defending-the-right-to-repair-an-argument-for-federal-legislation-guaranteeing-the-right-to-repair |url-status=live }}</ref>

To prevent refilling of empty [[ink cartridge]]s, manufacturers had started placing microchips counting fill levels and usage, rendering refills difficult or impossible. Reselling and refurbishing products was confirmed to be legal by the Supreme Court in 2017 in ''[[Impression Prods., Inc. v. Lexmark Int'l, Inc.]]''.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-05-30/u-s-supreme-court-curbs-patent-holders-power-to-block-resale | title = U.S. Supreme Court Curbs Patent-Holder Power to Block Resale | first1 = Greg | last1 = Stohr | first2 = Susan | last2 = Decker | date = May 30, 2017 | access-date = May 30, 2017 | work = [[Bloomberg L.P.]] | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170530161011/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-05-30/u-s-supreme-court-curbs-patent-holders-power-to-block-resale | archive-date = May 30, 2017 }}</ref> As of 2022, complaints about the longevity and repairability of printers remains.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Weatherbed |first=Jess |date=August 11, 2022 |title=Bricked Epson printers make a strong case for user repairability |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/8/11/23301272/epson-ink-pad-right-to-repair |access-date=May 11, 2024 |website=The Verge |language=en |archive-date=May 11, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240511170103/https://www.theverge.com/2022/8/11/23301272/epson-ink-pad-right-to-repair |url-status=live }}</ref>[[File:DEF CON 30 Right to Repair - Louis Rossmann and Joe Grand 24-2.png|thumb|Right to repair activists [[Joe Grand]] and [[Louis Rossmann]] speaking at [[DEF CON]] 30]]
In the early 2000s, the automotive industry defeated the [[Motor Vehicle Owners' Right to Repair Act|first proposal of a right to repair bill for the automotive sector]].<ref name="Hatta">{{cite journal |last1=Hatta |first1=Masayuki |title=The Right to Repair, the Right to Tinker, and the Right to Innovate |journal=Annals of Business Administrative Science |date=August 15, 2020 |volume=19 |issue=4 |pages=143–157 |doi=10.7880/abas.0200604a|s2cid=225397805 |doi-access=free }}</ref> While the National Automotive Service Task Force (NASTF), an organization supported by the automotive industry, established an online directory for accessing manufacturer information and tools in 2001,<ref>{{cite news |date=August 6, 2002 |title=Automotive Group Testifies Against Right to Repair Act Bill |url= |work=Autoparts Report |publisher=Gale Group Inc.|volume=15|issue=21}}</ref> a study conducted by the Terrance Group found that around 59% of independent repair services continued to struggle to get access to diagnostic tools and parts from manufacturers.<ref>{{cite book |title=How the clean air act affects auto repair |date=June 28, 2005 |pages=18–19 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H6eLPswsEVYC&dq=survey+terrance+group+access+spare+parts+2005&pg=PA18 |access-date=September 29, 2021 |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office |location=Washington|isbn=9780160754074 }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=May 2024}} The share of electronic components in the total bill of materials for a car also rose from 5% in the 1970s to over 22% in 2000.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Statista Research Department |date=February 5, 2021 |title=Automotive electronics cost as a percentage of total car cost worldwide from 1970 to 2030 |url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/277931/automotive-electronics-cost-as-a-share-of-total-car-cost-worldwide/ |access-date=July 26, 2021 |website=Statista |archive-date=April 20, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230420051526/https://www.statista.com/statistics/277931/automotive-electronics-cost-as-a-share-of-total-car-cost-worldwide/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The increasing hybridization of cars brought the need of special tools that a manufacturer only shared with authorized repair services.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Borg |first1=Kevin L. |title=Auto Mechanics: Technology and Expertise in Twentieth-Century America |date=2007 |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press |isbn=9780801894855 |location=Baltimore}}</ref>

A trend towards right to repair in automotive and other industries gained traction with more proposed laws and court decisions.<ref name="Hatta" /> While initially driven by [[automotive industry|automotive]] [[consumer protection|consumers protection]] agencies and the automotive after-sales service industry, the discussion of establishing a right to repair for any kind of industrially produced device gained traction as [[consumer electronics]] such as smartphones and computers became widely used, alongside advanced computerized integration in farming equipment. The movement was also backed by climate change activists aiming to reduce e-waste.<ref>{{cite web |last=Stanton |first=Chris |date=December 30, 2022 |title=The DIY D-Day A movement taking on the likes of Apple is winning a major battle for consumers. |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2022/12/the-right-to-repair-movements-biggest-battle.html |website=[[NY Magazine]] |access-date=December 29, 2022 |archive-date=March 8, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230308163548/https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2022/12/the-right-to-repair-movements-biggest-battle.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

