The first successful implementation of a right to repair came when [[Massachusetts]] passed the United States' first right-to-repair law for the automotive sector in 2012, which required automobile manufacturers to sell the same service materials and diagnostics directly to consumers or to independent mechanics as they used to provide exclusively to their dealerships. As a result, major automobile [[trade organization]]s signed a Memorandum of Understanding in January 2014 using the Massachusetts law as the basis of their agreement for all 50 states starting in the 2018 automotive year.<ref name="Weins">{{cite web | url = https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/02/you-gotta-fight-for-your-right-to-repair-your-car/283791/ | title = You Gotta Fight For Your Right to Repair Your Car | first = Kyle | last = Weins | date = February 13, 2014 | access-date = March 8, 2018 | work = [[The Atlantic]] | archive-date = June 22, 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180622193055/https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/02/you-gotta-fight-for-your-right-to-repair-your-car/283791/ | url-status = live }}</ref>

Companies like Apple, John Deere, and [[AT&T]] have lobbied against right to repair bills, and created a number of "strange bedfellows" from high tech and agricultural sectors on both sides of the issue, according to ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Fitzpatrick |first=Alex |date=June 22, 2017 |title=Hand Me That Wrench: Farmers and Apple Fight Over the Toolbox |url=https://time.com/4828099/farmers-and-apple-fight-over-the-toolbox/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303053545/http://time.com/4828099/farmers-and-apple-fight-over-the-toolbox/ |archive-date=March 3, 2018 |access-date=March 8, 2018 |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref> The tech industry has lobbied in opposition through groups like TechNet,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Said |first1=Carolyn |date=May 20, 2022 |title=Broken laptop? How California's right-to-repair movement is trying to make it easier to fix your electronics |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Broken-laptop-How-California-s-right-to-repair-17185453.php |access-date=May 31, 2022 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |location=[[San Francisco]]}}</ref> the Entertainment Software Alliance ("ESA").<ref>{{Cite web |last=Koebler |first=Jason |date=February 25, 2017 |title=The Video Game Industry Is Lobbying Against Your Right to Repair Consoles |url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/the-video-game-industry-is-lobbying-against-your-right-to-repair-consoles/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210216131243/https://www.vice.com/en/article/d7kak7/the-video-game-industry-is-lobbying-against-your-right-to-repair-consoles |archive-date=February 16, 2021 |access-date=August 9, 2021 |website=Vice (news) |language=en}}</ref> The [[Association of Equipment Manufacturers]] ("AEM") and their dealership counterparts the Equipment Dealers Association's 2018 Statement of Principles became the subject of media backlash when in January 2021 the promised means to make complete repairs had not been visibly available.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Koebler |first=Jason |date=February 18, 2021 |title=John Deere Promised Farmers It Would Make Tractors Easy to Repair. It Lied. |url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/john-deere-promised-farmers-it-would-make-tractors-easy-to-repair-it-lied/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210317072516/https://www.vice.com/en/article/v7m8mx/john-deere-promised-farmers-it-would-make-tractors-easy-to-repair-it-lied |archive-date=March 17, 2021 |access-date=August 9, 2021 |website=Vice.com |language=en}}</ref>

In late 2017, users of older [[iPhone]] models discovered evidence that recent updates to the phone's operating system, [[iOS]], were throttling the phone's performance. This led to accusations that Apple sabotaged the performance of older iPhones to compel customers to buy new models more frequently.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Kottasová |first1=Ivana |title=Apple is facing lawsuits over iPhone slowdown controversy |url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/01/12/technology/apple-iphone-slow-battery-lawsuit/index.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228044141/http://money.cnn.com/2018/01/12/technology/apple-iphone-slow-battery-lawsuit/index.html |archive-date=February 28, 2018 |access-date=July 14, 2018 |work=CNNMoney|last2=Toh|first2=Michelle|last3=Geier|first3=Ben}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Kirby |first=Jen |date=December 28, 2017 |title=Apple admitted it's slowing down certain iPhones |url=https://www.vox.com/2017/12/22/16807056/apple-slow-iphone-batteries |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715035917/https://www.vox.com/2017/12/22/16807056/apple-slow-iphone-batteries |archive-date=July 15, 2018 |access-date=July 14, 2018 |work=Vox}}</ref> Apple disputed this assumed intention, stating instead that the goal of the software was to prevent overtaxing older [[Lithium-ion battery|lithium-ion batteries]], which have degraded over time, to avoid unexpected shutdowns of the phone.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Warren |first1=Tom |last2=Statt |first2=Nick |date=December 20, 2017 |title=Apple confirms iPhones with older batteries will take hits in performance |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/12/20/16800058/apple-iphone-slow-fix-battery-life-capacity |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916181022/https://www.theverge.com/2017/12/20/16800058/apple-iphone-slow-fix-battery-life-capacity/ |archive-date=September 16, 2018 |access-date=March 8, 2018 |work=[[The Verge]]}}</ref> Furthermore, Apple allowed users to disable the feature in an iOS update but advised against it.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Vomiero |first=Jessica |date=March 30, 2018 |title=You can now disable the feature that lets Apple slow down your phone, but should you? |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4115331/apple-ios-update-disable-slow-iphone/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715042110/https://globalnews.ca/news/4115331/apple-ios-update-disable-slow-iphone/ |archive-date=July 15, 2018 |access-date=July 14, 2018 |work=[[Global News]] |language=en}}</ref> Additionally, Apple allowed users of affected iPhones to obtain service to replace batteries in their phones for a reduced cost of service ({{USD|29}} compared to {{USD|79}}) for the next six months.<ref>{{cite web |last=Stevens |first=Matt |date=December 28, 2017 |title=Accused of Slowing Old iPhones, Apple Offers Battery Discounts |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/28/business/apple-iphone-batteries.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622200225/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/28/business/apple-iphone-batteries.html |archive-date=June 22, 2018 |access-date=March 8, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> However, the "right to repair" movement argued that the best outcome would be Apple allowing consumers to purchase third-party batteries and possess the instructions to replace it at a lower cost.<ref>{{cite web |last=Koebler |first=Jason |date=December 21, 2017 |title=Apple's iPhone Throttling Will Reinvigorate the Push for Right to Repair Laws |url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/apple-iphone-throttling-right-to-repair/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180915185924/https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/a3nvmk/apple-iphone-throttling-right-to-repair |archive-date=September 15, 2018 |access-date=March 8, 2018 |work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]}}</ref>

In April 2018, the [[Federal Trade Commission]] sent notice to six automobile, consumer electronics, and video game console manufacturers, later revealed through a [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] request to be [[Hyundai Group|Hyundai]], [[Asus]], [[HTC]], [[Microsoft]], [[Sony]], and [[Nintendo]], stating that their warranty practices may violate the [[Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Kastrenakes |first=Jacob |date=May 1, 2018 |title=Microsoft, Nintendo, and Sony warned by FTC about potentially illegal product warranties |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/5/1/17308042/ftc-illegal-warranty-letters-warning-microsoft-sony-nintendo-asus-htc-hyundai |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705011035/https://www.theverge.com/2018/5/1/17308042/ftc-illegal-warranty-letters-warning-microsoft-sony-nintendo-asus-htc-hyundai |archive-date=July 5, 2018 |access-date=May 1, 2018 |work=[[The Verge]]}}</ref> The FTC specifically identified that informing consumers that warranties are voided if they break a warranty sticker or seal on the unit's packaging, use third-party replacement parts, or use third-party repair services is a deceptive practice, as these terms are only valid if the manufacturer provides free warranty service or replacement parts.<ref>{{cite web |last=Liao |first=Shannon |date=April 10, 2018 |title=FTC warns console and smartphone makers against limiting consumer warranties |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/10/17220462/ftc-reminds-companies-warranty-stickers-are-illegal |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615111624/https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/10/17220462/ftc-reminds-companies-warranty-stickers-are-illegal |archive-date=June 15, 2018 |access-date=April 10, 2018 |work=[[The Verge]]}}</ref> Both Sony and Nintendo released updated warranty statements following this notice.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kim |first=Matt |date=May 9, 2018 |title=Nintendo, Sony Update Their Warranty Following Warning From the FTC |url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/nintendo-sony-updates-their-warranty-following-warning-from-the-ftc |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630105815/https://www.usgamer.net/articles/nintendo-sony-updates-their-warranty-following-warning-from-the-ftc |archive-date=June 30, 2018 |access-date=May 9, 2018 |work=[[USGamer]]}}</ref>

In April 2018, US [[Public Interest Research Group]] issued a statement defending [[Eric Lundgren]] over his sentencing for creating the ‘restore disks’ to extend the life of computers.<ref>{{cite news |last=Carman |first=Ashley |date=April 25, 2018 |title=E-waste recycler must serve 15-month sentence for selling discs with free Microsoft software |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/25/17279190/microsoft-restore-disk-eric-lundgren-sentence-right-to-repair |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708133419/https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/25/17279190/microsoft-restore-disk-eric-lundgren-sentence-right-to-repair |archive-date=July 8, 2018 |access-date=May 25, 2018 |work=The Verge}}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=May 2024}}

In 2018, the exemption for making software modifications to "land-based motor vehicles" was expanded to allow equipment owners to engage the services of third parties to assist with making changes. These changes were endorsed by the [[American Farm Bureau Federation]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rogers |first=Kaleigh |date=January 31, 2017 |title=The 'Right to Repair' Movement Is Being Led by Farmers |url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/farmers-right-to-repair/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210210180541/https://www.vice.com/en/article/kbgzgz/farmers-right-to-repair |archive-date=February 10, 2021 |access-date=August 10, 2021 |website=Vice.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Koebler |first1=Jason |date=September 11, 2018 |title=Farmer Lobbying Group Sells Out Farmers, Helps Enshrine John Deere's Tractor Repair Monopoly |url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/california-farm-bureau-john-deere-tractor-hacking-right-to-repair/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201109040641/https://www.vice.com/en/article/kz5qgw/california-farm-bureau-john-deere-tractor-hacking-right-to-repair |archive-date=November 9, 2020 |website=Vice |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Koebler |first=Jason |date=October 25, 2018 |title=In Groundbreaking Decision, Feds Say Hacking DRM to Fix Your Electronics Is Legal |url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/1201-exemptions-right-to-repair/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026012458/https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/xw9bwd/1201-exemptions-right-to-repair |archive-date=October 26, 2018 |access-date=October 26, 2018 |work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]}}</ref> In its 2021 recommendations, the [[Library of Congress]] further extend the exemption, with favorable right-to-repair considerations for automobiles, boats, agricultural vehicles, and medical equipment, as well as modifying prior rules related to other consumer goods.<ref>{{cite web |last=Robertson |first=Adi |date=October 27, 2021 |title=The US Copyright Office just struck a blow for the right to repair |url=https://www.theverge.com/2021/10/27/22747310/us-copyright-office-dmca-section-1201-exemption-rulemaking-report |accessdate=October 27, 2021 |work=[[The Verge]] |archive-date=October 27, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211027140413/https://www.theverge.com/2021/10/27/22747310/us-copyright-office-dmca-section-1201-exemption-rulemaking-report |url-status=live }}</ref>

Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]], as part of her campaign for president, laid out plans for legislation related to agriculture in March 2019, stated her intent to introduce legislation to affirm the right to repair farm equipment, potentially expanding this to other electronic devices.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kelly |first=Makena |date=March 27, 2019 |title=Elizabeth Warren comes out in support of a national right-to-repair law |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/27/18284011/elizabeth-warren-apple-right-to-repair-john-deere-law-presidential-campaign-iowa |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327163823/https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/27/18284011/elizabeth-warren-apple-right-to-repair-john-deere-law-presidential-campaign-iowa |archive-date=March 27, 2019 |access-date=March 27, 2019 |work=[[The Verge]]}}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=May 2024}}

In August 2019, Apple announced a program where independent repair shops may have the ability to buy official replacement parts for Apple products. Several operators became Authorized under their "IRP" program but many smaller repair operators avoided the option due to legally onerous burdens.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Potuck |first=Michael |date=February 6, 2020 |title=Apple comes under fire for Independent Repair Program contract that lawyers are calling 'crazy' |url=https://9to5mac.com/2020/02/06/apple-independent-repair-program-criticism/ |access-date=August 10, 2021 |website=9to5Mac |language=en-US |archive-date=August 10, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210810151240/https://9to5mac.com/2020/02/06/apple-independent-repair-program-criticism/ |url-status=live }}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=May 2024}}

In the 2010s the trend of making one's repairs to devices spread from the east into the Western Europe.<ref name="Gault">{{cite web |last=Gault |first=Matthew |date=December 14, 2018 |title=Protesters Are Slowly Winning Electronics Right-to-Repair Battles in Europe |url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/protesters-are-slowly-winning-electronics-right-to-repair-battles-in-europe/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001152505/https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9k487p/protesters-are-slowly-winning-electronics-right-to-repair-battles-in-europe |archive-date=October 1, 2019 |access-date=October 1, 2019 |work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]}}</ref> In July 2017, the [[European Parliament]] approved recommendations that member states should pass laws that give consumers the right to repair their electronics, as part of a larger update to its previous [[European Ecodesign Directive|Ecodesign Directive]] from 2009 which called for manufacturers to produce more energy-efficient and cleaner consumer devices. The ability to repair devices is seen by these recommendations as a means to reduce waste to the environment.<ref>{{cite web |last=Matsakis |first=Louise |date=July 5, 2017 |title=The European Parliament Wants Europeans to Have the Right to Repair |url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/the-european-parliament-wants-europeans-to-have-the-right-to-repair/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001154011/https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9kwaa5/the-european-parliament-wants-europeans-to-have-the-right-to-repair |archive-date=October 1, 2019 |access-date=October 1, 2019 |work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]}}</ref> With these recommendations, work began on establishing the legal Directive for the EU to support the recommendations, and from which member states would then pass laws to meet the Directive. One of the first areas of focus was consumer appliances such as refrigerators and washing machines. Some were assembled using adhesives instead of mechanical fasteners which made it impossible for consumers or repair technicians from making non-destructive repairs. The right-to-repair facets of appliances were a point of contention and lobbying between European consumer groups and appliance manufacturers.<ref name="Gault" /> Ultimately, the EU passed legislation in October 2019 that required manufacturers of appliances to be able to supply replacement parts to professional repairmen for ten years from manufacture. The legislation did not address other facets related to right-to-repair, and activists noted that this still limited the consumer's ability to perform their own repairs.<ref>{{cite web |last=Harriban |first=Roger |date=October 1, 2019 |title=EU brings in 'right to repair' rules for appliances |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-49884827 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001021610/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-49884827 |archive-date=October 1, 2019 |access-date=October 1, 2019 |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> Sweden also offers tax breaks for people who repair their own goods.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Baum |first=Caroline |date=October 14, 2019 |title=Tinker tailors: the grassroots movement reclaiming the right to repair |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2019/oct/15/tinker-tailors-the-grassroots-movement-reclaiming-the-right-to-repair |access-date=July 15, 2024 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

The EU also has directives toward a [[circular economy]] which are aimed toward reducing greenhouse gas emissions and other excessive wastes through recycling and other programs. A 2020 "Circular Economy Action Plan" draft included the electronics right to repair for EU citizens to allow device owners to replace only malfunctioning parts rather than replace the entire device, reducing electronics waste. The Action Plan included additional standardization that would aid toward rights to repair, such as common power ports on mobile devices.<ref>{{cite web |last=Peltier |first=Elian |date=March 12, 2020 |title=Europe Wants a 'Right to Repair' Smartphones and Gadgets |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/12/world/europe/eu-right-to-repair-smartphones.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313235333/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/12/world/europe/eu-right-to-repair-smartphones.html |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |access-date=March 14, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>

In the midst of the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], where medical equipment became critical for many hospitals, iFixit and a team of volunteers worked to publish and make accessible the largest known collection of manuals and service guides for medical equipment, using information crowdsourced from hospitals, medical institutions and sites like Frank's Hospital Workshop. iFixit had found, like with consumer electronics, some of the more expensive medical equipment had used means to make non-routine servicing difficult for end-users and requiring authorized repair processes.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Goode |first=Lauren |date=May 19, 2020 |title=Right-to-Repair Groups Fire Shots at Medical Device Manufacturers |url=https://www.wired.com/story/right-to-repair-medical-equipment-ifixit/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200520071312/https://www.wired.com/story/right-to-repair-medical-equipment-ifixit/ |archive-date=May 20, 2020 |access-date=May 21, 2020 |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=August 10, 2021 |title=Introducing the World's Largest Medical Repair Database, Free for Everyone |url=https://www.ifixit.com/News/41440/introducing-the-worlds-largest-medical-repair-database-free-for-everyone |access-date=August 10, 2021 |website=iFixit |language=en |archive-date=August 10, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210810151240/https://www.ifixit.com/News/41440/introducing-the-worlds-largest-medical-repair-database-free-for-everyone |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[2020 Massachusetts Question 1]] passed to update the previous measure on automobile repair to include electronic vehicle data.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Janzer |first1=Cinnamon |date=December 15, 2020 |title=What Massachusetts' New Right-to-Repair Law Means for Small Auto Repair Shops |url=https://nextcity.org/daily/entry/what-massachusetts-new-right-to-repair-law-means-for-small-auto-repair-shop |access-date=September 29, 2021 |website=nextcity.org |language=en |archive-date=April 12, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230412102028/https://nextcity.org/daily/entry/what-massachusetts-new-right-to-repair-law-means-for-small-auto-repair-shop |url-status=live }}</ref> Before it could come into effect, in June 2023, the federal [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] instructed manufacturers to ignore the 2020 Massachusetts law, asserting it was preempted by federal law because opening telematics to other organizations could make cars more vulnerable to computer hackers. (Both claims are disputed by Massachusetts in the lawsuit.)<ref>{{cite news |author=Hiawatha Bray |date=June 14, 2023 |title=Federal government warns carmakers not to comply with Mass. right-to-repair law |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2023/06/14/business/feds-warn-carmakers-not-comply-with-mass-right-to-repair-law/ |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref>

In May 2021, the [[Federal Trade Commission]] (FTC) issued a report "Nixing the Fix" to Congress that outlined issues around corporations' policies that limit repairs on consumer goods that it considered in violation of trade laws, and outlined steps that could be done to better enforce this. This included self-regulation by the industries involved, as well as expansion of existing laws such as the [[Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act]] or new laws to give the FTC better enforcement to protect consumers from overzealous repair restrictions.<ref>{{cite web |last=Porter |first=Jon |date=May 7, 2021 |title=FTC report blasts manufacturers for restricting product repairs |url=https://www.theverge.com/2021/5/7/22424363/ftc-repair-restrictions-report-nixing-the-fix-smartphones-automakers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210507102032/https://www.theverge.com/2021/5/7/22424363/ftc-repair-restrictions-report-nixing-the-fix-smartphones-automakers |archive-date=May 7, 2021 |accessdate=May 7, 2021 |work=[[The Verge]]}}</ref>

In July 2021, the Biden administration issued an executive order to the FTC<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Goode |first=Lauren |date=July 9, 2021 |title=Joe Biden Wants You to Be Able to Fix Your Own Damn iPhones |url=https://www.wired.com/story/biden-executive-order-right-to-repair/ |access-date=August 9, 2021 |magazine=Wired |language=en-US |issn=1059-1028 |archive-date=August 9, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210809234030/https://www.wired.com/story/biden-executive-order-right-to-repair/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and the Department of Agriculture<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ahl |first=Jonathan |title=Right To Repair Mandate From Biden Might Help Farmers Fix Their Own Equipment |url=https://www.harvestpublicmedia.org/post/right-repair-mandate-biden-might-help-farmers-fix-their-own-equipment |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210809234044/https://www.harvestpublicmedia.org/post/right-repair-mandate-biden-might-help-farmers-fix-their-own-equipment |archive-date=August 9, 2021 |access-date=August 9, 2021 |website=www.harvestpublicmedia.org |language=en}}</ref> to widely improve access to repair for both consumers and farmers. The executive order to the FTC included instructions to craft rules to prevent manufacturers from preventing repairs performed by owners or independent repair shops.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Breuninger |first1=Kevin |last2=Feiner |first2=Lauren |date=July 9, 2021 |title=Biden signs order to crack down on Big Tech, boost competition 'across the board' |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/07/09/biden-to-sign-executive-order-aimed-at-cracking-down-on-big-tech-business-practices.html |accessdate=July 9, 2021 |work=[[CNBC]] |archive-date=March 6, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230306013624/https://www.cnbc.com/2021/07/09/biden-to-sign-executive-order-aimed-at-cracking-down-on-big-tech-business-practices.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sullivan |first1=Kate |last2=Fung |first2=Brian |last3=Klein |first3=Betsy |date=July 9, 2021 |title=Biden signs sweeping executive order that targets Big Tech and aims to push competition in US economy |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/07/09/politics/biden-big-tech-executive-order/index.html |accessdate=July 9, 2021 |work=[[CNN]] |archive-date=April 14, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230414172619/https://www.cnn.com/2021/07/09/politics/biden-big-tech-executive-order/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref> About two weeks later, the FTC voted unanimously to enforce the right to repair as policy and to look to take action against companies that limit the type of repair work that can be done at independent repair shops.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kelly |first=Makena |date=July 21, 2021 |title=FTC pledges to fight unlawful right to repair restrictions |url=https://www.theverge.com/2021/7/21/22587331/right-to-repair-apple-iphone-ftc-lina-khan-open-meeting |accessdate=July 21, 2021 |work=[[The Verge]] |archive-date=April 18, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230418203337/https://www.theverge.com/2021/7/21/22587331/right-to-repair-apple-iphone-ftc-lina-khan-open-meeting |url-status=live }}</ref>

Apple announced in November 2021 that it would be allowing consumers to order parts and make repairs on Apple products, initially with iPhone 12 and 13 devices but eventually rolling out to include Mac computers.<ref>{{cite web |last=Iyengar |first=Rishi |date=November 17, 2021 |title=Apple will let iPhone users repair their own devices |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/11/17/tech/apple-iphone-right-to-repair/index.html |accessdate=November 17, 2021 |work=[[CNN]] |archive-date=November 17, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211117142238/https://www.cnn.com/2021/11/17/tech/apple-iphone-right-to-repair/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=May 2024}} Reception to the program has been mixed, with Right to Repair advocate [[Louis Rossmann]] seeing the program as a step in the right direction, but criticized the omission of certain parts, and the need to input a serial number before ordering parts.<ref>{{Citation |title=Apple's self service repair program got released, let's check it out |date=April 27, 2022 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=agG108sxkyo |access-date=August 29, 2022 |language=en |archive-date=August 29, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220829143034/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=agG108sxkyo |url-status=live }}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=May 2024}}

In 2021, France created a [[Repairability#French repairability index|repairability scoring system]] that took inspiration from [[IFixit|iFixit's]] scorecard. France expressed its intent to merge it into a 'Durability index' that also considers how long items are expected to last.<ref name="Stone" />

In 2022, Apple started enabling customers to repair batteries and screens.{{Citation needed|date=July 2024}} Additionally, Apple has prevented companies from repairing or refurbishing Apple's products without their permission. These action have irritated consumers who believe Apple is against the right to repair.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Mikolajczak |first=Chloé |date=June 4, 2020 |title=Apple crushes one-man repair shop in Norway's Supreme Court, after three-year battle |url=https://repair.eu/news/apple-crushes-one-man-repair-shop/ |access-date=August 23, 2023 |website=Right to Repair Europe |language=en-US |archive-date=August 23, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230823131248/https://repair.eu/news/apple-crushes-one-man-repair-shop/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2022, [[Framework Computer]], [[Adafruit Industries|Adafruit]], [[Raspberry Pi]], among other computer systems, started sharing [[3D printing|3D-printable]] models for replacement parts.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Purdy |first=Kevin |date=December 20, 2022 |title=Framework, Noctua, and other brands add official 3D models to Printables |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2022/12/framework-noctua-and-other-brands-add-official-3d-models-to-printables/ |access-date=December 20, 2022 |website=Ars Technica |language=en-us |archive-date=January 3, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230103013529/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2022/12/framework-noctua-and-other-brands-add-official-3d-models-to-printables/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

On December 28, 2022, New York Governor [[Kathy Hochul]] signed into law the [[Digital Fair Repair Act]], nearly seven months after it had passed the [[New York State Senate|state senate]]. The law established the right of consumers and independent repairers to get manuals, diagrams, and original parts from manufacturers, although ''[[The Verge]]'', ''[[Engadget]]'', and ''[[Ars Technica]]'' noted that the bill was made less vigorous by way of last-minute changes that provided exceptions to original equipment manufacturers. It will apply to electronic devices sold in the state in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Faulkner |first=Cameron |date=December 29, 2022 |title=New York breaks the right to repair bill as it's signed into law |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/12/29/23530733/right-to-repair-law-new-york-tech-hochul-oems-parts |access-date=December 29, 2022 |website=The Verge |language=en-US |archive-date=February 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230224015157/https://www.theverge.com/2022/12/29/23530733/right-to-repair-law-new-york-tech-hochul-oems-parts |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=New York's governor signs watered-down right-to-repair bill |url=https://www.engadget.com/new-york-right-to-repair-law-kathy-hochul-184654713.html |access-date=December 29, 2022 |website=Engadget |date=December 29, 2022 |language=en-US |archive-date=March 6, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230306005326/https://www.engadget.com/new-york-right-to-repair-law-kathy-hochul-184654713.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Cunningham |first=Andrew |date=December 29, 2022 |title=New York governor signs modified right-to-repair bill at the last minute |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2022/12/weakened-right-to-repair-bill-is-signed-into-law-by-new-yorks-governor/ |access-date=December 29, 2022 |website=Ars Technica |language=en-us |archive-date=May 25, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230525234405/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2022/12/weakened-right-to-repair-bill-is-signed-into-law-by-new-yorks-governor/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

John Deere announced in January 2023 that it was signing a [[memorandum of understanding]] with the [[American Farm Bureau Federation]] agreeing that American farmers had the right to repair their own equipment or have it serviced at independent repair shops in the United States. Consumers and independent repair centers would still be bound against divulging certain trade secrets, and cannot tamper or override emission control settings, but are otherwise free to repair as they see fit.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Miller |first=Monica |date=January 8, 2023 |title=US farmers win right to repair John Deere equipment |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-64206913 |access-date=March 7, 2023 |work=BBC News |language=en-GB |archive-date=June 4, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230604090628/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-64206913 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2023, three business professors cautioned that right-to-repair laws by themselves, could have unintended consequences including incentivizing companies to create cheaper products that are lower-cost and less repairable or durable, or raise the initial sale price of the item.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Yang |first1=Luyi |last2=Jin |first2=Chen |last3=Zhu |first3=Cungen |date=January 19, 2023 |title=Research: The Unintended Consequences of Right-to-Repair Laws |url=https://hbr.org/2023/01/research-the-unintended-consequences-of-right-to-repair-laws |access-date=May 11, 2024 |work=Harvard Business Review |issn=0017-8012 |archive-date=June 5, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240605135622/https://hbr.org/2023/01/research-the-unintended-consequences-of-right-to-repair-laws |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Jin |first1=Chen |last2=Yang |first2=Luyi |last3=Zhu |first3=Cungen |date=February 2023 |title=Right to Repair: Pricing, Welfare, and Environmental Implications |url=https://pubsonline.informs.org/doi/10.1287/mnsc.2022.4401 |journal=Management Science |language=en |volume=69 |issue=2 |pages=1017–1036 |doi=10.1287/mnsc.2022.4401 |issn=0025-1909 |url-access=subscription |archive-date=May 11, 2024 |access-date=May 11, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240511052512/https://pubsonline.informs.org/doi/10.1287/mnsc.2022.4401 |url-status=live }}</ref>

The U.S. Copyright Office, as part of the tri-annual review of exemptions for the [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act]], approved an exemption for bypassing technical controls for retail-level commercial food preparation equipment for the purposes of repair and maintenance. Notoriously, the inability for third-party repairs of such equipment had been the cause of numerous [[McDonald's ice cream machine]]s being out-of-service, as the manufacturer, [[Taylor Company]], had only allowed themselves to repair these machines.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2024/10/25/24279371/mcdonalds-ice-cream-machines-right-to-repair-copyright | title = McDonald's busted ice cream machines can now be fixed — legally | first = Emma | last = Roth | date = October 25, 2024 | accessdate = October 25, 2024 | work = [[The Verge]] | archive-date = October 27, 2024 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20241027090549/https://www.theverge.com/2024/10/25/24279371/mcdonalds-ice-cream-machines-right-to-repair-copyright | url-status = live }}</ref>

==Enacted legislation==
Some jurisdictions have enacted right-to-repair legislation.

=== Canada ===
On November 7, 2024, Bill C-244 received royal assent and became law, making Canada the first country to enact a national right-to-repair law.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Chan |first=Katherine |date=April 3, 2025 |title=Right to repair in Canada: You can now fix your own stuff |url=https://www.millerthomson.com/en/insights/technology-ip-and-privacy/whats-new-canada-copyright-law/ |access-date=July 8, 2025 |website=Miller Thomson |language=en-US |archive-date=July 8, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250708150154/https://www.millerthomson.com/en/insights/technology-ip-and-privacy/whats-new-canada-copyright-law/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== European Union ===
Adopted on May 30, 2024, the [https://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-9-2023-0316-AM-086-086_EN.pdf European Union's Right to Repair Directive (R2RD)] requires manufacturers to offer repair services that are both efficient and affordable, while also making sure consumers are aware of their repair rights.<ref>{{Cite web |date=April 23, 2024 |title=Right to repair: Making repair easier and more appealing to consumers {{!}} News {{!}} European Parliament |url=https://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20240419IPR20590/right-to-repair-making-repair-easier-and-more-appealing-to-consumers |access-date=October 14, 2024 |website=www.europarl.europa.eu |language=en |archive-date=October 9, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241009044605/https://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20240419IPR20590/right-to-repair-making-repair-easier-and-more-appealing-to-consumers |url-status=live }}</ref> Specifically, according to the European Commission’s summary of the Directive (2024/1799), manufacturers of products covered by EU reparability requirements and listed in the Directive’s annex must offer repair “within a reasonable time” and “for a reasonable price,” and are prohibited from using contractual clauses or hardware/software techniques that hinder repair of covered goods unless objectively justified. 

The directive also introduces a voluntary European Repair Information Form that repairers can provide (usually free of charge on request), enabling consumers to compare repair conditions, price and timing; completed forms then remain valid for at least 30 days.<ref>{{cite web |title=Common rules promoting the repair of goods and amending related EU legislation |website=EUR-Lex (Summaries of EU legislation) |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/EN/legal-content/summary/common-rules-promoting-the-repair-of-goods-and-amending-related-eu-legislation.html |access-date=December 12, 2025 |archive-date=December 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20251215215058/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/EN/legal-content/summary/common-rules-promoting-the-repair-of-goods-and-amending-related-eu-legislation.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In addition, Directive 2024/1799 amends the EU sales-of-goods rules so that when a consumer chooses repair (rather than replacement) within the seller’s liability framework, the legal guarantee must be extended once by one year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Common rules promoting the repair of goods and amending related EU legislation |website=EUR-Lex (Summaries of EU legislation) |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/EN/legal-content/summary/common-rules-promoting-the-repair-of-goods-and-amending-related-eu-legislation.html |access-date=December 12, 2025 |archive-date=December 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20251215215058/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/EN/legal-content/summary/common-rules-promoting-the-repair-of-goods-and-amending-related-eu-legislation.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Moreover, to support market access to repair services, the directive provides for a European online platform for repair (with national sections or linked national platforms), including the possibility to list repairers and, optionally, sellers of refurbished goods and community-led initiatives, such as repair cafés. The common EU interface is to be developed by July 31, 2027, and the platform is expected to become fully operational by January 1, 2028.<ref>{{cite web |title=Directive (EU) 2024/1799 (selected provisions on the European online platform) |website=EUR-Lex |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/dir/2024/1799/oj/eng |access-date=December 12, 2025 |archive-date=December 1, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20251201092505/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/dir/2024/1799/oj/eng |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Common rules promoting the repair of goods and amending related EU legislation |website=EUR-Lex (Summaries of EU legislation) |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/EN/legal-content/summary/common-rules-promoting-the-repair-of-goods-and-amending-related-eu-legislation.html |access-date=December 12, 2025 |archive-date=December 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20251215215058/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/EN/legal-content/summary/common-rules-promoting-the-repair-of-goods-and-amending-related-eu-legislation.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Member States must transpose the directive by July 31, 2026, with application from July 31, 2026.<ref>{{cite web |title=Common rules promoting the repair of goods and amending related EU legislation |website=EUR-Lex (Summaries of EU legislation) |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/EN/legal-content/summary/common-rules-promoting-the-repair-of-goods-and-amending-related-eu-legislation.html |access-date=December 12, 2025}}</ref>

Previously, the right to repair in the EU was regulated by the [https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/dir/2019/771/oj Sale of Goods Directive] and the different product-specific Commission Regulations provided under the [https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A02009L0125-20121204 Ecodesign Directive].

===United States===
In the United States, the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) has examined repair restrictions in the context of consumer protection and competition policy. The 2021 report to Congress ([https://www.ftc.gov/system/files/documents/reports/nixing-fix-ftc-report-congress-repair-restrictions/nixing_the_fix_report_final_5521_630pm-508_002.pdf "Nixing the Fix"]) describes common forms of repair restriction, such as limits on access to parts, tools, and proprietary diagnostic software, and analyzes their consumer and competitive effects.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nixing the Fix: An FTC Report to Congress on Repair Restrictions |publisher=Federal Trade Commission |date=May 2021 |url=https://www.ftc.gov/reports/nixing-fix-ftc-report-congress-repair-restrictions |access-date=December 12, 2025 |archive-date=December 10, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20251210081236/https://www.ftc.gov/reports/nixing-fix-ftc-report-congress-repair-restrictions |url-status=live }}</ref>

